<paper id="1863150103"><title>Model-Checking for Real-Time Systems</title><year>1995</year><authors><author org=", Aalborg University" id="2146581609">Kim Guldstrand Larsen</author><author org=", Uppsala University," id="2011261465">Paul Pettersson</author><author org=", Uppsala University," id="2124415778">Wang Yi</author></authors><n_citation>175</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>84675887</reference><reference>1529601677</reference><reference>1536783297</reference><reference>1541064517</reference><reference>1552719844</reference><reference>1637976039</reference><reference>1728798265</reference><reference>1865562238</reference><reference>1934074768</reference><reference>2101508170</reference><reference>2114092850</reference><reference>2129335898</reference><reference>2153439859</reference><reference>2167668895</reference><reference>2176837466</reference><reference>2398303742</reference><reference>2573837267</reference></references><venue id="1189194555" type="C">Fundamentals of Computation Theory</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-60249-6_41</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.45631">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Graph</keyword><keyword weight="0.60073">Model checking</keyword><keyword weight="0.45987">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.54776">Binary decision diagram</keyword><keyword weight="0.4762">Theoretical computer science</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Efficient automatic model-checking algorithms for real-time systems have been obtained in recent years based on the state-region graph technique of Alur, Courcoubetis and Dill. However, these algorithms are faced with two potential types of explosion arising from parallel composition: explosion in the space of control nodes, and explosion in the region space over clock-variables.</abstract></paper>